<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1048]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,308,662,688]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Remarks:</emphasis>
—Mexican populations of this species were always found growing with other bryophytes. In one of the most crowded patches, some rosettes of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephani (1916:" authorityYear="1003" box="[630,742,698,725]" class="Anthocerotopsida" family="Anthocerotaceae" genus="Anthoceros" kingdom="Plantae" order="Anthocerotales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Anthocerotophyta" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis box="[630,742,698,725]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">A. subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were formed by very small plants of less than 
<quantity box="[1267,1332,698,725]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in capsule height and thallus diameter. Some also exhibited an unusual erect morphology of the thallus, similar to the thallus morphology that has been reported in 
<taxonomicName authority="Kashyap (1915: 9)" authorityName="Kashyap" authorityPageNumber="9" authorityYear="1915" box="[582,922,770,797]" class="Arachnida" family="Segestriidae" genus="Ariadna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erectus">
<emphasis box="[582,696,771,797]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">A. erectus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kashyap, S. R." box="[706,922,770,797]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref6336" refString="Kashyap, S. R. (1915) Morphological and biological notes on new and little known West-Himalayan liverworts III. New Phytologist 14 (1): 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="1915">Kashyap (1915: 9)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Asthana, A. K. &amp; Srivastava, S. C." box="[939,1262,770,796]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 158" refId="ref4458" refString="Asthana, A. K. &amp; Srivastava, S. C. (1991) Indian hornworts (A taxonomic study). Bryophytorum Bibliotheca 42: 1 - 158." type="journal article" year="1991">Asthana &amp; Srivastava 1991</bibRefCitation>
). In these dwarf plants, the surface of the thallus was barely large enough for the base of the involucre to fit. This dwarf morphotype was probably a result of space and resource availability and may have also been affected by a fungal infection, since red hyphae were found within the gametophyte of some of these plants.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1048]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
Previous reports of this species from Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Asthana, A. K. &amp; Srivastava, S. C." box="[692,1012,914,940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 158" refId="ref4458" refString="Asthana, A. K. &amp; Srivastava, S. C. (1991) Indian hornworts (A taxonomic study). Bryophytorum Bibliotheca 42: 1 - 158." type="journal article" year="1991">Asthana &amp; Srivastava 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Hasegawa, J." box="[1027,1218,914,941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="173 - 177" refId="ref6026" refString="Hasegawa, J. (1998) Taxonomic status of Anthoceros subbrevis Haseg. and taxonomy of its allied taxa. Bryological Research 7 (6): 173 - 177. https: // doi. org / 10.24474 / bryologicalresearch. 7.6 _ 173" type="journal article" year="1998">Hasegawa, 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Peng, T. &amp; Zhu, R. - L." box="[1233,1444,914,941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="21 - 35" refId="ref6586" refString="Peng, T. &amp; Zhu, R. - L. (2013) A revision of the genus Anthoceros (Anthocerotaceae, Anthocerotophyta) in China. Phytotaxa 100 (1): 21 - 35. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 100.1.3" type="journal article" year="2013">Peng &amp; Zhu 2013</bibRefCitation>
) document slightly larger thallus size (
<quantity box="[554,647,950,977]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6 mm</quantity>
in diameter) and larger spores (35–45 µm) than those of Mexican plants (thallus up to 
<quantity box="[290,376,986,1013]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
and spores of 26.6–42.1 μm), but spore morphology is very similar to that illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Peng, T. &amp; Zhu, R. - L." pageId="4" pageNumber="97" pagination="21 - 35" refId="ref6586" refString="Peng, T. &amp; Zhu, R. - L. (2013) A revision of the genus Anthoceros (Anthocerotaceae, Anthocerotophyta) in China. Phytotaxa 100 (1): 21 - 35. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 100.1.3" type="journal article" year="2013">Peng &amp; Zhu (2013)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[331,402,1022,1048]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
